vectorData.altText: 26. Arteries to the urinary bladder, uterus and vagina are derived from the _____________ trunk of the _____________ _____________ artery. (three words, each separated by one space)
22A   The Anterior Trunk of the Internal Iliac Artery

In males, each anterior trunk gives rise to a(n):
superior and inferior vesical arteries, supplying the bladder, ureter, seminal vesicles and prostate gland.
inferior gluteal artery, which contributes to the blood supply of the gluteal region.

middle rectal artery, supplying the rectum, along with the superior rectal artery from the inferior mesenteric artery and the inferior rectal arteries from the internal pudendal arteries.
obturator artery, which enters the medial compartment of the thigh via the obturator canal.
internal pudendal artery, which exits the pelvis via the greater sciatic foramen and enters the perineum via the lesser sciatic foramen to supply perineal structures.

In females:
in place of an inferior vesicle artery, women have a vaginal artery, which supplies the vagina and adjacent parts of the bladder, urethra and rectum.
the uterine artery is a major branch that runs in the base of the broad ligament to the cervix, where it anastomoses with the vaginal artery. There the vaginal artery turns to ascend along the lateral aspect of the uterus, and runs along the uterine tubes, where it ends in an anastomosis with the ovarian artery.
That’s right! The anterior trunk of the internal iliac artery gives rise to the arteries that supply these viscera.
